"People are subjected to human rights violations.
They are stopped on the roads because of the color of their skin, they are beaten and killed, "Rod Chapel, president of the National Association for the Advancement of the Colored Population of Missouri, told Kansas City Star.
"We hear complaints often, like never before."
This is the first warning of this kind declared by the organization in relation to the US state.
The group referred to incidents such as the blacking of black students on racial grounds at the University of Missouri and the death of twenty-eight-year-old Tori Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in suspicious circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gasoline on a state trip, and the Missouri police arrested him without charge of a crime.
The warning also mentions a recent report from the Missouri Attorney General's Office, according to which the probability of being stopped on the road for black drivers is 75 percent higher than for whites.
"The purpose of the warning is to ensure that people are aware of the situation and have warned their relatives and friends and colleagues about what can happen in Missouri," Chapel said.
"People should be somehow prepared, whether they will take money for bail or tell their relatives that they are traveling across the state."
According to the latest data from the FBI's hate crime report, 100 hate crimes were recorded in Missouri in 2015, making the state the sixteenth in the state in terms of the number of such violations.
Also, the travel warning is a response to the new Missouri law, after which it will be more difficult to bring a case against a legal entity in connection with housing or labor discrimination.
Earlier, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) announced warnings for travelers to Texas and Arizona after these states adopted new immigration control laws according to which local law enforcement agencies were ordered to arrest people for violating immigration laws, which, according to the ACLU, should have increased the number of racial checks.
