Nothing sacred?
Now Trump's White House set his sights on the Statue of Liberty.
The most reliable sign of regime change is when he begins to fight against the statues.
Americans understand this no worse than all the rest - hence the deliberately theatrical demolition of the statue of Saddam Hussein in Firdos Square in Baghdad in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the key ideologists of Trump's government, no doubt knew what he was doing when he brought a symbolic ax over the Statue of Liberty during a fierce dispute with CNN journalist Jim Acosta about the president's proposals for a drastic reduction in legal migration.
Let's be honest, Miller did not attempt the statue itself.
The hordes of owners of pleasure boats and artists depicting the Statue of Liberty would lynch him if he tried to do it.
But he attempted on its meaning, and especially on the meaning that was attributed to her in 1903, 17 years after the completion of the monument, when poems by Emma Lazarus were added to the pedestal.
As Miller grumbled at Acosta: "I do not want to go deep into history here, but the Statue of Liberty is ... a symbol of American freedom that illuminates the world.
The poem that you are talking about was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty. "
Miller correctly stated the facts, but as he himself said, it's not really about history.
This is about the current sound of Lazarus' striking words, the only ones in which the state invites not all immigrants, but the poorest: "Your tired, your poor, / your crowds dreaming to breathe freely, / The unfortunate scum of your abundant shores."
Never before had the "unfortunate garbage" been so visible on our screens.
Miller did not study literary criticism - he made it clear that in America Trump these people are not expected.
This debate about the meaning of the statue is part of a broader political and cultural war: it's really a dispute about the meaning of America.
Lazarus - and her friends, who fought to put her words on the socle of the statue after her death - knew very well that they were doing a completely political act.
The sculpture was intended to indicate the connection between the French and American republics with the help of a banal classic figure - the female image of Freedom.
Lazarus changed her meaning: in her poem the female figure is no longer abstract, she has a voice.
And she received a completely different name: the Mother of the Exiles.
The combination of the poem and the image was a brilliant feminist move and a crushing attack against American nativism.
And how Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the right though to change it back.
The thunderous Rush Limbo, a kind of John the Baptist who ushered in the advent of Trump, in 2010 argued that Freedom does not invite anyone, rather it is an early neo-conservative, carrying the flame of America to the world lying in darkness: "Freedom is moving forward.
It carries the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not needed to illuminate the way in the United States. "
Against the usual Limbaugh here really hit the mark.
The meaning of the statue depends solely on the angle of view.
The great creative achievement of Lazarus was to see her as she was seen by emaciated, unhappy, but hopeful people on the decks of ships after a long and often heavy voyage.
It means to literally look at the world through the eyes of people who seek refuge and a chance for a better life.
Her statue responds to them with the words of hope and hospitality that they dream of hearing.
And, of course, this is not the prospect that Miller and Trump will ever want to recognize.
Their torch is needed not to light the way, but to kindle hatred, which is the only source of their strength.
