Blocking critics on Facebook: you do not need to be promoted to public office if you are not ready to listen to criticism from voters
The founder of our country understood what a critical press is.
Americans loved George Washington, but that did not stop them from criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
Of course, the criticism irritated him.
But he did not shut his mouth to his critics.
Because back in 1783 Washington said: "You can take freedom of speech and we, deaf and dumb, will be led like a sheep to the slaughterhouse."
Now I will go to the governor of Maryland, Larry Hogan, who should try to be more like Washington.
Hogan's subordinates blocked and erased the posts of at least 450 people who expressed their views on his official Facebook page.
And this week the American Civil Liberties Union filed a lawsuit against him for this.
The subordinate governors called this claim insignificant, and the comment on the Internet was written in the spirit of "so what?".
"It's just Facebook," many will say.
But this is also important.
And this is especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He is a surprisingly popular Republican governor in a predominantly democratic state.
He is in second place in the approval rating among 50 governors of the country.
Hogan is not a stubborn reactionary.
He demonstrated a firm hand in managing the state and adherence to his principles.
He also cleverly uses Facebook as the primary way of communicating with his constituents and jokes on his page showing his bald head after chemotherapy.
Therefore, blocking people who come to the governor's page - which is declared as an official public forum and conducted by the administration's employees with taxpayer money - is unnecessary and ultimately harmful.
In an interview with the Washington Post, spokeswoman Amelia Ches defended the governor's actions, arguing that blocking comments is simply their moderation.
But it's too easy to use the image of trolls, spammers and hayters who are angry on the Internet.
"The Post" talked to some of the real people Hogan had blocked.
And these are real people, not trolls - a teacher, a businessman, a pastor, who turn to their elected leaders.
All of them say that their comments were respectful, informative and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, appealing to the fact that Hogan is a Catholic.
Lakshmi's lawyer Sarma Ramana from Bowie, Maryland, did not express hatred, but asked about hate crimes.
"I wrote a polite comment that I was disappointed by the lack of his reaction to hate crimes and other recent news," she wrote in the comment section on the article in the Post.
"I also do not like the idea that when a lot of people leave comments on the same topic, some immediately say that this is a so-called cheating, rather than admit that they are dealing with a large group of dissatisfied citizens."
What the governor's subordinates call a "concentrated spam attack", others, probably, would be called an "active life position."
In the era of Facebook, it's easy to edit your image, simply by blocking critics or erasing negative comments.
This is much less dusty work than before, when it required sending people, collecting and burning newspapers with critical editorials or arresting and muffling protesters.
But this is exactly what is happening now, only in the figure.
Hoheng is not the first official to be criticized for not wanting to listen to Facebook and other social networks.
President Trump was sued by Twitter users who were banned in his Twitter account.
One of the first, pivotal decisions on this topic was taken this week in Virginia.
According to the US District Judge from Alexandria James K. Kesheris, the chairman of the Loudon County Supervisory Board violated the First Amendment by busting the voter in his account in Facecbook.
And in Kentucky, Republican Governor Matt Bavin was challenged by the American Civil Liberties Union for his behavior on Facebook and Twitter.
This should not be so difficult.
During the era of Washington, the era of available postage cost has made about the same revolution as the Internet today.
From 1776 to 1800 the number of newspapers grew fourfold, and the authors of anonymous letters severely brought down its authority.
And even then Washington dealt with anonymous trolls.
People with pseudonyms "Yurikola", "Valerius", "Belizarius" and "Porcius" wrote letters to newspapers mocking Washington's decision.
According to historical documents collected by the online project "Documents of George Washington," his cabinet was filled with petitions that criticized his position on the Treaty of Friendship, Trade and Navigation.
But he did not try to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and speech lies at the very foundation of our state.
And true leadership means acceptance.
