While preparing dinner, Bardeen Degei does not use a stove.
She even rarely uses a pot.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of Paniyai County in the rebellious Indonesian province of Papua, the housewife usually simply places the sweet potatoes, which here is called the "note", right into the hearth.
Half an hour later the charred tuber is removed and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the earthen floor - she has no furniture - and it is here that she does her housework, such as washing clothes with muddy water from a nearby swamp.
A bucket is a bucket in a room without a roof.
She is the youngest of four wives of her husband, and therefore she was not instructed to work in the field.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many men from this village are unemployed, many drink, and yet there are soldiers.
"No one dares to walk around the village after five in the evening," she says.
This is a rare opportunity to look at daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a dubious referendum when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote, publicly raising their hands before the occupying forces.
The current movement, in favor of independence from the Netherlands, quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which maintains tight control over the region, preventing foreign journalists and human rights activists.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, and the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is a city as remote as the one abandoned, the road here includes an hour and a half flight from Jayapura, the administrative center of the province, in Nabire, and then a five-hour jolt on a rented car.
There is no public transport here.
The city with a population of about 19,000 people consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, corrugated steel roofs are rusted in a variety of rusty shades.
Here got very few of the Indonesians, not to mention the journalists, and almost none of the foreigners.
Before the arrival of the Christian missionaries of the Papuans, the Pago worshiped a god named Uga Tamee.
There were other changes.
"It was unusual for us to wear these clothes," says Degei, pointing to his bright, hand-woven turban, dark skirt and bright shirt.
"Previously, we only wore leaves on the body."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, 28% of its population lives below the poverty line, and the child mortality and literacy among the worst in Asia.
But still it is Indonesian golden land.
The world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by the Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran company, is only sixty miles from Paniyah, a high-mountain province about the size of New Jersey, home to 153,000 people.
Only in 2015 the company "Freeport" produced gold and copper here by about $ 3.1 billion.
In addition, Papua boasts forest resources, the cost of which is estimated at 78 billion dollars.
These riches, however, entail one misfortune for the Papuans, ensuring that the powerful armed forces of Indonesia retain their suffocating presence here.
According to the New York Times investigation in 2005, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid almost $ 20 million to local soldiers and units, including up to $ 150,000 to one officer.
The demands of greater autonomy on the part of the Papuans threaten the existence of this golden vein and are ruthlessly suppressed.
According to human rights defenders, since 1969, Indonesian military forces have killed more than 500,000 Papuans, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, massacres in the highlands of Papua inhabited by indigenous people in the seventies can be considered genocide.
Only last year the Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
"We will lose everything," the report, published in 2016 by the Diocese of Brisbane, contains evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as summary executions, torture - especially as reported in another report, rape and electric shock - and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
"It's hard to count the number of victims, because the incidents take place every week," says Andreas Harsono, who studies in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
The nuts dragged on, as Papua's resources attracted an influx of migrants from other parts of Indonesia.
The region's 3.5 million population is 83% Christian, but demographic indicators change as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the densely populated Indonesian islands of Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javan shops, "varungi", sell fried chicken and a mixture of vegetables "gado-gado", served with peanut sauce.
Local residents are trying to withstand competition.
"Migrants began to sell chicken and vegetables on the traditional market cheaper than the indigenous people of Papua," explains Abet You, a twenty-four-year-old Paniyai who moved to Jayapura, the province's administrative center, because of her work.
"Because of this, the indigenous people of Papua - mama-mama (women) of Papua - have lost their market."
Indonesian President Joko Vidodo, popularly known as Djokovi, vowed to address inequality and violations of rights in Papua during his presidential campaign in 2014.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, the former carpenter enlisted the support of 27 of the 29 districts of Papua, including Paniyah.
But in Papua almost nothing has changed, and the locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts are broken, because in 2014 we voted for Djokovi, expecting that he will fulfill our hopes for the restoration of justice," says Yo.
In fact, just two months after the October inauguration, Djokovi Paniay experienced a tragedy.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children was on the street and sang Christmas carols at the fire in Enarotali, when two Indonesian soldiers rushed out of the dark on a motorcycle.
The frightened children told them that they should turn on the lights.
According to local pastor Javedt Tebay, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and after a while returned with four soldiers.
According to victims and eyewitnesses, soldiers who were drunk, chased children and beat them with rifle butts.
Then one of the soldiers shot a group of children.
One child, sixteen-year-old Julianus Yaimo, was so badly beaten that he fell into a coma.
A couple of hours later, someone lit a nearby government building of the election commission, and the next day the situation escalated.
About a thousand Papuan men, women and children gathered in a football field in front of the local police station and the military command center to demand justice.
They brought with them ritual hunting bows and performed a white, dance of Papuan tribe me Pago: they ran around in circles and depicted bird singing.
Some protesters began to throw stones at the police station and the military base.
When the situation became hot, the soldiers were ordered through internal radio communication: "If the crowd protests more than three times, shoot them," as it sounded, according to an official document seen by TIME correspondents, but which was not published in local media.
The fifty-six-year-old Eremias Kayame, the head of the Kego Koto district in Enarotali, sensed the approach of danger and called for calmness, turning to the crowd with a request to disperse to their homes.
Nobody wanted to listen to him.
"When I turned around, a bullet hit me in my left wrist," he told TIME magazine, standing on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still does not know who fired, but says that the bullet flew from the ranks of the assembled soldiers.
"There was a crowd, there were a lot of shots," he adds.
The local resident Alfius Jouva was hit three times, as his cousin, who witnessed the shooting, tells.
"I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him," Johannes told TIME magazine, which, like many Indonesians, uses only one name.
"I saw that he was dead ... I kissed him."
General Yotja Mende, Senior Inspector of the Papua Police, told reporters that his officers merely "defended" their base, because they were attacked.
"We must defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us," Commissioner Pujo Sulistio said in 2015, the Papua police spokesman.
"This is a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed, and much more was wounded.
The news of the murders reached Jakarta only the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokovy spoke in Jayapur with an ardent speech in which he expressed his condolences to the families of the victims and vowed to tackle the issue of the historical abuse of power in Papua.
"I want this situation to be settled immediately so that it will never happen again in the future," he said.
In October 2016, the Minister of Security, Vieranto, said he would establish an extra-judicial organization to put an end to historical human rights violations.
But almost immediately went the excuses.
"Most of the violations occurred long ago.
Some of them took place in the nineties or at the beginning of the zero ones.
The fact is that we definitely want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures that need to be passed, "he said.
Then Wiranto gave up his words, speaking with TIME magazine on June 5 in Jakarta, and said he did not plan to establish an organization to handle complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said: "Everything will be decided through the court."
Viranto, who was accused by the United Nations of "crimes against humanity" in connection with the death of more than 1,000 people during the bloody vote for the independence of East Timor in 1999, said that 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua had already been resolved, including the Paniyah incident.
Families of victims from Paniyah met similar statements with a grim suspicion.
"Over the past three years, I was questioned four times, but there was absolutely no change," says Johannes.
"I'm tired."
He says that years later he still lives in fear.
"I'm scared," he says.
"I'm afraid that the military will arrest me, I'm afraid they'll shoot me."
His brother Jakobus also expressed the opinion that the residents of Paniyah are afraid to discuss the incident.
He said that he was beaten by the military after he helped to bury the four victims.
"After we buried the bodies, the military came for me," he says.
The shooting did not stop.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired at villagers in the nearby Deyan district of Paniyai.
During the clash between the villagers and the manager of the construction company, who refused to help take the unconscious man to the hospital, one person was killed and 17 more were injured, including children.
A man, twenty-four-year-old Ravianus Dove, drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on his way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested before the office of the construction site owned by the company.
According to the police, villagers threw stones at officers who responded with warning shots.
But local residents claim that the mobile brigade (Indonesian special forces) began to shoot at the crowd and killed one person.
"We were in such a panic, we are afraid of retribution," - told the magazine TIME twenty-nine-year-old Domingung Badia, who lives near the hospital and saw how hastily the wounded were delivered.
"I was hiding in my house for two days."
Parliament Deyayi demanded that the officers involved in the incident be called to account, and the mobile police brigade was recalled from this region.
Paniyai has always been a sore spot for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development causes dissatisfaction with the tribes of me, moni, tribute and damal scattered throughout the greens of central highland areas of Papua.
Many have joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), an insurgent army that claims to protect the rights of the Papuans by arranging sporadic attacks and raids on kidnapping Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top OPM leaders come from Paniyai, including Thadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoia.
In retaliation in recent years, thousands of people were arrested in Paniyai and groundlessly detained by the military under the pretext of "protecting national independence".
Some never returned.
Among the population of Papua, Paniyah is considered a "sad, forgotten place".
Poverty increases discontent.
A small portion of rice, sold in Enarotali, is too expensive for local residents.
Bread is in the same exact degree inaccessible.
People here grow everything they eat: basically, a note, as well as some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Agriculture is the work of women, each of which can take care of four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
Usually they save most of the crop for the family, and the rest is sold in the local market.
Ten tuber notes are worth only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, the economic disparity between indigenous Papuans and new migrants has increased, which came in large numbers after the introduction of new flights to Nabire airport.
Few existing vacancies usually go to more educated and wealthy migrants.
Papuans rarely have enough money or the necessary skills to run their own competitive business.
"Young people do not want to stay in the village ... because there is no work, no money," says John Gobai, chairman of the tribal council Paniy.
Isolation keeps Papua away from the views of the rest of the world.
In addition, restrictions on the work of international media remain harsh.
Earlier this year, French journalists Frank Eskyudi and Basil Lonshan were deported from Papua for "lack of coordination with relevant organizations" despite the fact that they were given rare permits for video filming.
According to Felima Keene, deputy director for Asia of the organization Human Rights Watch, the promises made during the pre-election campaign of Djokovy to lift restrictions on the work of the media in order to promote transparency and development have not been fulfilled.
"Now foreign journalists trying to report from the rebellious eastern Indonesian provinces, Papua and West Papua, face new dangers: visa denials and blacklisting," he said in a statement.
Lack of attention from the press means that international pressure on the Government of Indonesia is mainly limited to the immediate neighbors of Papua.
In March, six Pacific countries - Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and the Solomon Islands - requested the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "various and widespread violations" in Papua, including shooting at Paniyay.
The same countries in the past supported OPM.
A spokesman for the Indonesian Foreign Ministry, Arramanath Nasir, dismissed the group's statement, informing reporters in Jakarta that "There is still a democratic system in Indonesia and there is a free press, so it would be difficult to hide evidence of human rights violations."
Local residents want more foreign governments to pay attention to the situation.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by the Netherlands Ambassador for Human Rights Kiys Van Baar, visited Jayapur on May 4, the locals broke the silence, praying: "We want freedom," according to a source who was also present at the meeting, but wished to remain anonymous.
In Indonesia, in 2019, a new presidential election will be held, but the Papuans say that they are unlikely to vote again for Djokovi.
"Djokovi is a man who has good intentions, but he is surrounded by people involved in the shooting at Paniyai," says Gobai, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Djokovi to know that the inhabitants of Paniyah, in addition to being in the shadow of a threat from the greedy army, are mired in poverty, and education and health care are in a pitiful state.
Gobay says that the inhabitants of Paniyai, like other Papuans, consider their voice given to Djokovi as a duty that he must pay.
"They do not need money, they just want justice," he says.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the shooting in Paniyai carried out the last symbolic act of disobedience: they buried the body of one of the victims in a plot of land directly opposite the police and military station.
Knowing that justice will probably never triumph, they, at least, will not allow the guilty to forget about their crimes.
"They killed a member of our family," says Yakobus, without raising his head.
"What else could we do?"
