Head of EPA Pruitt refuses to postpone the implementation of the rules adopted by Obama on reducing emissions
The day after the lawsuit of 15 states, the head of the Environmental Protection Agency canceled his decision to postpone the implementation of the rules adopted by Obama, designed to reduce emissions of substances that pollute the air and lead to the formation of smog.
Pruitt explained his decision by saying that now his agency is more than in previous administrations, listening to the needs of environmental regulators in individual states.
He did not mention the lawsuit against his previous position, filed with the federal appeals court.
The dispute spun around the October 1 deadline, to which the states must ensure compliance with the 2015 Ozone Standards at ground level.
In June, Pruitt announced that he would defer compliance for one year to give his department more time to study the plan and avoid "inconsistency with local solutions or obstacles to economic growth."
Pruitt, who before being appointed President Trump for his current position, was the Attorney General of Oklahoma, was long known as a consistent opponent of tightening environmental regulations.
After moving to Washington, Pruitt repeatedly blocked or postponed the introduction of norms that the chemical or gas-oil industry was against.
Unexpected change of course on Wednesday is another legal defeat of the course taken by Pewitt to return to previous standards.
Last month, the federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the head of the EPA exceeded his authority, trying to delay the implementation of the Obama administration's rule requiring oil and gas companies to monitor and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released on Wednesday evening, Pruitt suggested that, having drastically changed course on ozone standards, he simply fulfilled the EPA's responsibility to cooperate with the states in the complex process of timely implementation of new standards.
"Under previous administrations, the EPA often could not meet the deadlines, then waited for claims from activist groups and others and discussed the timing of the settlement," said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen claims against the EPA in his previous position.
"We do not believe in regulation through litigation, and we take the deadlines seriously.
We are also serious about our charter and the power that it gives us. "
However, the EPA statement said that Pruitt may at some point again use its "powers to delay and other statutory powers" to make sure that the norms are "jcyjdfys on a clear course and on all available information."
Republicans in Congress insist on a broader review of the rules relating to ozone.
The bill, approved by the House of Representatives last month, seeks to postpone the implementation of the 2015 rules for at least eight years.
The Senate has not yet voted on this issue.
Attorney General of New York Eric Schneiderman, who led the coalition of states that filed a lawsuit this week against the EPA, said the group intends to continue legal pressure.
"The changes in the EPA course - after our lawsuits - are an important victory in the struggle for health and safety of 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans directly affected by the smog that covers their cities," Sneijderman said.
The suit of New York was joined by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont and Washington, and the District of Columbia.
Ozone at ground level occurs when ordinary pollutants from machinery, power plants, oil refineries and chemical plants and other sources enter the atmosphere in response to sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause serious breathing problems in sensitive people, leading to thousands of premature deaths per year.
Health advocates and environmentalists welcomed the unexpected change in Pruitt's course.
