Murder at Morse Ford: activists lose Lynch courts on stage to call for justice
"Ford Mercury" in 1948 drove past the audience in the village of Monroe in the state of Georgia and rushed to the small bridge Morse Ford.
When the car, in which there were four black passengers and a white driver, drove up to the bridge, a group of white men with guns barred her way.
Chief - a middle-aged man in a suit in a thin strip - tightened a cigar and looked through the windshield.
Those sitting inside trembled with fear.
"We need this nigga, Roger!" The man snapped.
"Get him out of the car!"
Piercing wails broke the silence when a young black man was dragged from the front seat.
Fortunately, this terrible scene, which took place on July 22, is just a dramatization.
But when the neck of the "Roger" threw a noose, almost all the audience really held their breath.
Since 2005, activists are returning to the Morse Ford Bridge to re-play the night when in 1946 the Kukluklasses lynched two black couples - Roger and Dorothy Malk and George and May Murray Dorsey.
No one was convicted of these murders.
"It's amazing that for all these years no one has been arrested - although we see them side by side, although we know who they are," says Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize the production.
"This is a blot on our history and it's a stone on our souls."
71-year-old Brooks is a former member of the Congress of Georgia, who has struggled for his human rights all his life.
For him, the play is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to the inhabitants of Monroe that injustice has not been corrected.
"We want an investigation, we want to complete, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice," he says.
"We can not go on to healing and reconciliation until we reach justice."
The coroner covers the body of one of the victims of lynching at Mors Ford on July 27, 1946.
According to the FBI materials received by NBC News, more than 50 people in Monroe and neighboring counties were suspected of involvement in lynching.
But no one was ever charged.
Although the suspects remained free for decades, human rights activists say that in the city they always knew two related motives of lynchers: politics and sex.
In April 1946, the ruling of the Supreme Court for the first time allowed black citizens to vote in the primaries, which were to be held that summer.
Approximately during the same election, according to FBI reports, the black-skinned Roger Malcolm struck in a fight with the knife of Barnett Hester, a white landowner - apparently because of a woman.
Brooks says that, according to rumors spreading in the city, Hester was sleeping with Malcolm Dorothy's wife, and that the child she was to give birth was not from her husband.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a large white landowner, paid $ 600 bail to rescue Malcolm from prison.
He went to prison with Dorothy and their cousins May Murray and George Dorsey.
But when they drove from prison and drove up to the Morse Ford Bridge, a crowd of lynchers surrounded the car.
"It turns out that he organized and commanded the killings of Harrison," - such a conclusion is made in one of the reports of the FBI.
"It is also clear that there was a collusion between law enforcement agencies of the state and the city, who not only participated in the murders, but also destroyed the evidence and concealed the identity of the witnesses."
Brooks calls it shorter.
"It was an attempt on the voting rights," he said.
"They were all killed to send a black signal to the city: if you register and vote, you will be the same."
For almost ten years, Cassandra Green has been directing an annual spectacle that reproduces the lynching at the Morse Ford bridge.
Her performance is obvious, it captures the viewer and narrates about that deep racism, which, as many would like to consider, there is no more in America.
It's hard to watch and even harder to turn away, but Green believes that this is the main thing.
"We do not want to talk about the Lynch courts, because they show us our own ugliness," she says.
"But I can not build a relationship with you if you do not hear me or hear what I experienced."
Rehearsals of this year's performance began in June, and on the first day of almost 30 actors - a dozen white, the rest black ones - gathered in the room and listened to the review of the play polished over the years.
Wade Marbo was a director along with Green.
For several years he played the role of the main member of the clan, but says that the role has not become easier.
"It seems to me that I got dirty, because it's not the kind of person that I am," Marbo says.
"But I believe that it is very important to remember this story, because we do not want to return at that time."
In the room, actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Raskona, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, repeat their roles.
Spectal begins with the fact that Malcolm, furious that Hester is sleeping with his wife Dorothy, screams and pushes him.
"I said, nigga, get out of my house!".
Shouts of Raskona in response.
A blow is heard.
And at the same time, all (at least all black actors) burst into laughter.
Green laughs loudest.
"What is" - asks Ascona.
He is concerned and embarrassed.
I'm overacting?
"No," Green says through his laughter.
"I just do not think that whites then said 'nigga'."
"Yes, yes," one of the black performers laughs.
"You have to make a solid 'r'".
And the energy in the room is changing too: discomfort is replaced by a feeling of comradeship.
All should do everything correctly, not only for the sake of the play, but also for the sake of the memory of four people killed.
The scene begins again.
This time, when Raskona speaks the word "n", it turns out to be sharp and sharp.
No man laughs.
The performance ends cruelly and quickly.
Shouts, shots, and then silence.
A woman in mourning black clothes stands over the bodies of actors and performs a sad song of Billy Holiday "Strange Fruit".
Her voice is interrupted by the word.
A hundred yards from her, fifty spectators are wiping tears and sweat from their eyes.
Among the audience is almost equal number of black and white.
One couple came from Ithaca, New York to see the show, many live very close.
They all endured the heavy stiflingness of Georgia for almost eight hours, while Brooks led them on a pilgrimage to the graves of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Until that moment, murders remained only a story, but now, when they are standing in the same place where people lynched, it seems that their ghosts are hovering right there in the air.
When the last note of the song fades, Green invites people to come closer and examine the bodies.
Children bend over to their heads, touch the paint, depicting blood, and motionless bodies and whisper something to each other.
"They're not really dead," one small boy mumbles, as if to remind himself of this.
After a few minutes Green thanks the audience, and suddenly everything ends.
Actors throw the ropes off their necks and wipe their tears.
Bradshaw embraces Marbo, a man in a suit who played the main Kuklukklanovtsa.
Nick Raskona embraces two other actors and suddenly, crying, falls into their arms: the emotional load of the play finally fell upon him.
"It's all right," whispered one of the women.
"We know that your heart is good.
You had a reason for this. "
Later spectators sit down to have supper together with actors.
At the same table, a white couple from Atlanta is animatedly discussing the play with the black couple they just met.
Deniz Daplinski hardly finds words to describe what she feels after the performance.
"It's hard to listen to these horrible, terrible words, and the actions of ... people who look like you, and who do it because they look like you," she says.
"After that, I think that lynching is still happening," she adds, "only now it's called what the police shoots."
In the other corner of the room, Tyrone Brooks took over the general attention, who remembers his work as a human rights advocate for food.
He says that he has already begun to plan the next year's performance.
"The production inspires us, because it not only describes the horror of what we experienced, but also teaches us," he says.
"Because if you do not learn from this lesson, it can happen again.
Those who do not study their history, who do not know their history, are doomed to repeat it. "
