New test results are published to assess the age of asylum seekers in Sweden
The latest test results of asylum seekers in Sweden, who were subjected to a new method of medical age evaluation, show that more than 80 percent of the tested persons were rated as over 18 years of age, but not all trust the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish national forensic medicine agency (Rttsmedicinalverket) started testing earlier this year.
They were designed to make the age assessment in the asylum procedure more accurate after the Swedish Migrationsverket was criticized for not being able to determine the real age of some refugees who claimed to be underage.
At the moment, Migrationsverket sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the Forensic Agency has now published the results of 2,481 tests for the period between mid-March and July 31, 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) of the test subjects were rated as people 18 years of age or older, and for another 25 cases, the forensic agency estimated that the test person is "probably a person of 18 years of age or older".
In the case of 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person "is probably less than 18".
Tests are conducted only in cases when the age of a person is in doubt.
According to Johan Grensson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results are consistent with the results over the past months.
"We do not see much difference with the statistics over the past months, the numbers are quite appropriate," he told The Local.
The high proportion of cases in which people were assessed as having reached the age of 18 does not necessarily indicate that asylum-seekers lied about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and reported that in 442 cases "most likely, the age of the tested 18 years or more."
However, after reviewing 581 published results, the newspaper "Svenska Dagbladet" found that in 243 cases a person openly declared that he was performing 18 this year.
The method of conducting medical age evaluation, which consists in making an x-ray of wisdom teeth and tomography of the knee joints and giving it to an analysis of dentists and radiologists, also caused criticism in some instances.
One of the skeptics is the endocrinologist from the Karolinska Institute Claude Marcus, part of whose work is assessing the biological maturity of people to determine if they have gone through puberty earlier or later than usual.
"I had reasons to think about this, and I do not think that we need to use the measurement methods that are used now.
The biological age is thus very inaccurately determined.
If we can not define it with confidence, we should not pretend that we can, "he told the Metro newspaper.
However, Grenssen from the Forensic Medicine Agency was in favor of the accuracy of the tests: "In general, we can say that the risk of mistakenly accepting the child as an adult is small.
