"FFP" was introduced by Michel Platini after his election as President of UEFA in 2007.
The former French footballer believed that clubs climbing into huge debts in their pursuit of success, in fact, cheated and risked ruin in the event that banks or owners stopped financing.
In 2011, "FPP" stopped focusing on the debts of clubs and instead switched to tracking their losses.
As a result of this change, the business model originally used by Roman Abramovich in Chelsea in 2003 - to buy a club with good potential, and then earn a lot in order to improve the team and create a global brand - has become a difficult plan.
During this three-year evaluation period, exciting 2018, clubs can suffer losses of 30 million euros.
