The order and places of the oath will be determined by the president
Where and how new Russian citizens will swear allegiance to the Russian Federation, the president will determine - such amendments to the second reading in the relevant law were developed by the State Duma Committee on Legislation and State Building.
A week ago, the deputies planned to directly determine the order of taking the oath in law.
From the solemn oath, children under the age of 18 will be released, as well as incapacitated, follow the amended text of the amendments to the bill "On Citizenship of the Russian Federation" (available to Izvestia), which the committee will consider on July 11 before the second reading at its meeting.
The idea to introduce the oath when joining the citizenship of the Russian Federation instead of formal signing of documents, President Vladimir Putin supported on June 6 during a meeting with State Duma Speaker Vyacheslav Volodin.
The deputies drafted this idea in the form of an amendment to the second reading in a bill that would cancel the decision to grant citizenship to those who subsequently were convicted of a number of crimes of a terrorist or extremist nature: for example, for public calls for terrorism or for publicly justifying it in the media or on the Internet (Part 2, Article 205.2 of the Criminal Code); and also for hijacking a plane, train or water transport;
According to the draft law, his logic was this: when a person signs a document for citizenship, a person signs under the promise to comply with Russian legislation - embarking on the path of extremism, he violates this promise.
The bill was introduced in April by Duma faction leaders Vladimir Vasiliev (United Russia), Gennady Zyuganov (Communist Party of the Russian Federation), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergei Mironov (Fair Russia) and State Duma Speaker Vyacheslav Volodin.
On May 19, the deputies adopted it in the first reading.
Last week, the State Duma Committee on State Construction and Legislation approved the text of the bill for the second reading, but now it has been reworked.
Now it says that the order of taking the oath will be established by the president of the Russian Federation.
Earlier, parliamentarians were going to describe the procedure directly in the law "On Citizenship of the Russian Federation," stating that the ceremony should take place in a solemn atmosphere before the state emblem and the Russian flag in the presence of a representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, it was not clear from the text of the bill where such an event should take place - the list of places where the emblem of the Russian Federation may be placed is regulated by the relevant federal constitutional law.
These include courts, offices of heads of state bodies of subjects, municipalities, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive bodies, etc.
Most likely, it could have been registrars.
Speaking solemnly, people wishing to obtain Russian citizenship will be after officials verify their documents.
But a Russian passport will be received by a person only after he takes the oath, follows from the revised text.
A week ago, the draft stated that the oath should precede the signing of the decree.
The updated text says that Russia will be sworn with 18 years, not with 14.
A rule has been preserved, according to which legally incapacitated or severally capable persons will be released from taking the oath, as well as those who can not pronounce, read or autographically sign the text of the oath.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to release from this procedure and "other persons",
Also, in the updated draft law, a special procedure for the admission of citizens of Ukraine to Russian citizens is considered, which are considered to be native speakers of the Russian language.
They will have to officially renounce Ukrainian citizenship, having provided for this purpose an appropriate application to the authorized body of Ukraine.
A notarized copy of the application will need to be handed over to Russian officials.
Refusal of "another's" citizenship, as now, will not be required, if it is stipulated by the international agreement or if it is impossible "due to reasons beyond the control of the person".
A corresponding amendment to the law was proposed by a group of deputies, among whom the first vice speaker of the State Duma Ivan Melnikov (Communist Party of the Russian Federation), Natalia Poklonskaya, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Airat Farrakhov (all - United Russia).
I think that many of you know that it is impossible to obtain a certificate from Ukraine, it is simply impossible.
Accordingly, a lot of people are waiting for the decision of their fate about the citizenship of the Russian Federation, "Pavel Krasheninnikov (EP), head of the Duma committee on state construction and legislation, explained on the eve.
In addition, the text clarified that the restrictions on the employment of certain positions for foreigners will not apply to those who have written off the "other" citizenship and handed over the former passport to the Russian Ministry of Internal Affairs, but "for reasons beyond his control" he was not considered a citizen of another country.
Now foreigners are forbidden to occupy posts in the municipal service, to be hired for facilities and organizations whose activities are related to ensuring Russia's security.
Also, a person with dual citizenship or a residence permit of another country can not become a deputy of the State Duma or a member of the Federation Council.
It is planned that the law should enter into force on September 1, 2017, by that time the necessary by-laws must be ready.
