Starting in September, patients will have access to a "revolutionary" drug for HIV prevention after the Battle of the High Court on funding the drug from the National Health Service.
The National Health Service of England announced that pre-exposure prevention of HIV (PREP), a tablet taken before sex, which has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in at-risk individuals by an average of 86 percent, will now be provided by the health service during the initial three-year trial period to approximately 10,000 people.
She agreed to finance the trial after the Court of Appeal upheld the High Court ruling last year stating that the National Health Service has the ability to pay the PrEP, despite her statements that it should be funded by local authorities.
This step, which was announced on Thursday, was named "the most important innovation" by the president of the National Health Service of England Simon Stevens, and the National Office for the Control of AIDS Spread (NAT) called it "turning point".
Before the full launch of the program throughout England by April 2018, the venereological dispensaries in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield are among the first to start registering people, and even more dispensaries will join the program in October.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a course of drugs from HIV taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
As studies have shown, PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV infection among people at risk.
At reception PrEP before sex in an organism of the person sufficient quantity of the certain preparations to prevent infection with a HIV-infection.
Such drugs can be taken daily or not later than two hours before sex.
Patients eligible to receive the drug are homosexual and bisexual men, transgender people and people whose partners are HIV-positive and do not receive successful treatment.
Dispensaries will select suitable participants who agreed to participate in the study, including men, women, transgender people and those whose partners are not aware whether their HIV status is being held back by antiretroviral therapy.
