Judges are offered protection from the chairmen
The Presidential Council for Human Rights (HRC), on behalf of Vladimir Putin, developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The HRC proposes to limit the powers of the chairmen of the courts and introduce their electivity.
For courts of appeal and cassation instances, the HRC wants to introduce special districts that will not be tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court should also present its proposals within the framework of the presidential mandate.
The HRO has completed the development of proposals that will strengthen the independence of Russian justice.
This work was conducted by the HRO on behalf of Vladimir Putin on January 3, 2017, which the president gave after meeting with council members.
At a meeting with members of the council on December 8, 2016, some cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as problems of public control in places of detention of citizens were discussed (see "Kommersant" on December 9).
The result of the work of the HRO was 25 proposals, which concern both issues of ensuring the independence of judges and identifying judicial errors, as well as financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin's human rights defenders is to limit the powers of the chairmen of courts to enhance the independence of the remaining judges.
If the candidate for the position of a judge has successfully passed the competition and received the support of the judiciary, the chairman of the court, according to the HRO, should present him to the appointment, not having the right to refuse, as the law now allows.
It is also proposed to deprive the president of the right to distribute cases between judges.
Do it, experts say, can be a specially written computer program.
The HRC also believes that the chairman has no right "to predetermine the results of the judge's qualification, initiate his involvement in disciplinary proceedings, and make decisions on the establishment of additional material benefits."
At the same time, the presidential council considers it necessary to move to "the election of the chairmen of the courts by the judges themselves" and "grant them powers for a relatively short period of time with mandatory rotation."
Now all chairmen of courts (from republican to district) are appointed for six years by the president on the proposal of the chairman of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
To protect judges from the pressure of regional administrations, the HRO proposes to organize a new appeal and cassation in the courts of general jurisdiction.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The HRO says that "it is necessary to ensure the organization of separate courts of appeal and cassation instances not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, but in judicial districts."
Experts take as a basis the practice of arbitration courts.
With them, there are "judicial districts" that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but guarantee greater independence from regional officials due to this, which makes use of "telephone law" difficult.
The HRO proposes that the world judges be strengthened by people's assessors in order to consider with their participation certain "categories of civil and administrative cases."
For example, the deprivation of parental rights, the restoration of work, the protection of honor and dignity, the deprivation of a driver's license, etc.
"These are only our proposals," the member of the HRO, judge of the Constitutional Court, retired Tamara Morshchakova, explained to Kommersant.
She also recalled that the president's assignment applied not only to the HRO, but also to the Supreme Court (Supreme Court), which had not yet disclosed its proposals.
The time for fulfilling the commission from the Armed Forces (among the co-executors is the Prosecutor General's Office and the Commissioner for Human Rights in the Russian Federation) there is still.
Reporting to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of justice is ensured in the Russian Federation, Vyacheslav Lebedev, chairman of the Armed Forces, is due before September 1.
To live a high life: a half-story and cunning design techniques turned this little apartment into Earls Court into a spacious dwelling
Joanne Lee, a former banker interested in real estate repairs, moved from a spacious house in Knightsbridge in 2014 to an apartment in Earls Court.
The apartment is located on the first floor of a nice model house in the style of Queen Anne, and in favor of the new design says that Joan did not pick up her things and moved again.
"I used to live with my ex-Knightsbridge in a much larger area," Joan says.
"I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earls Court, and here were the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered a price on the same day. "
Since the first viewing, an apartment of 1,000 square feet has undergone a complete renovation.
Originally it was a one-bedroom apartment with a complex layout - to get into the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen - and Joanna wanted to add storage space and a semi-floor to get the most out of the generous height of the ceilings.
"I wanted high ceilings, large windows, lots of light.
Those were my requirements, "she says.
To this end, she hired Erfan Azadi from the architectural and design studio Duck & Shed, located in Notting Hill, to use 12.5-foot-high ceilings and create a dwelling that would not only be a successful project, but would be suitable for Joan's life.
The ceiling was not high enough to arrange two rooms one above the other, so the architectural task was to create a semi-floor, where you could stand in full growth.
Erfan had to think creatively to cope with the brief.
"Working with steel structures is very difficult," he explains.
"We needed to arrange the rooms so that they were one above the other, and did not have to bend.
It was necessary not just to build a simple platform, but to bend the structures so that they were at the right height and allowed to use the rooms from above and from below. "
This decision allowed Erfan to arrange two full-sized rooms one above the other in the allotted space - and many more interesting.
From the half-story through the vintage copper light window from the "Retrouvius" you can see the chic living room below.
Mirror furniture with golden trim, silver accents and vintage lighting from Serge Mui set the style of the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding entertainment, space and light.
A short corridor is framed by mirrors to make it seem longer.
In the kitchen, the mirrored security panel seems to be a window to another room.
At the entrance, mirrored cabinets serve to store all the dishes of Joan.
To create a feeling of more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can block the kitchen when not in use.
In the folding kitchens there is nothing new.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it is a sliding door, like in a garage.
"Engineering was involved here," Erfan says of the steel-reinforced wood-panel panel door.
"It's equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily."
Thanks to the intelligent use of space and storage space, Joan received an additional 16 square meters, an additional bedroom and an improved layout.
"In the end, the floor area is exactly what you will sell, that is, what your real estate is valued," Erfan says.
"Roughly speaking, a real estate agent will enter and make calculations based on the floor area."
Here they were able to increase the floor area using quality materials that give the space a touch of luxury.
"Materials are what we touch, so they help create an emotional bond with the house," Erfan says.
"Nobody falls in love with the electrical wiring in the walls.
It is important, but it does not affect the strings of our hearts. "
This is a testament to the fact that due to good design and increased footage, the apartment can turn from something ordinary into something amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you can decide to stay.
