The verdict of Michel Carter for the messages that led to the suicide of Conrad Roy
A resident of Massachusetts was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for using her text messages and phone calls to encourage the suicide of her boyfriend Conrad Roy.
Michel Carter, who is now 20 years old, will have to serve 15 months of his time in jail and another 5 years of probation.
Carter in June was found guilty of the manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide July 13, 2014.
Roy's father said at a hearing on Thursday: "My family is heartbroken.
My son was my best friend. "
Carter was allowed to remain at large until the appeal.
She threatened a maximum of 20 years, but her lawyers said that she and Roy suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red pants and a cream blouse, listened to the sentence standing, hands clasped and eyes lowered.
"By her actions, she killed Konrad Roy," the prosecutor told the court.
"She interrupted his life to improve her.
She did not admit responsibility, "she said.
"She did not show remorse."
But attorney Carter said that it was "a tragic case, of which she deeply regrets."
However, Judge Lawrence Monis said that, in his opinion, her "age, level of maturity or even mental illness did not significantly affect her actions."
The prosecutor read the statements of the mother of Roy Lynn Roy, which says: "not a single day passed when I would not mourn the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and the way I manage it - I try to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will remain with us forever, "it says.
Sister Roy Camdin Roy said that she was persistently pursued by the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become his aunt's children.
"To lose the person who has been with me always since my birth is a pain that will remain with me for the rest of my life," she said.
This case is likely to become a legal precedent, as there is no law in Massachusetts that would provide for the responsibility for counseling a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in the car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The case drew the attention of the whole country when it became known that he had been pushed to the suicide of the message of Carter.
"You can hang yourself, jump from the roof, I do not know how to stab myself with a knife, there are many ways," she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death, when he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before suicide she wrote: "You must do this, Conrad" and "You only need to turn on the ignition, and you will be free and happy."
Judge Monis said that Carter wanted to get attention with the help of Roy's death, and forbade her to communicate with the press to prevent her from getting what she wanted.
The opinions of lawyers on this issue were divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 for murdering her British roommate in Italy and acquitted two years later.
The 30-year-old Knox published her own opinion in the Los Angeles Times, stating: "Michel Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison."
