Murder of the journalist underlines that in Mexico it is becoming more dangerous.
Employees of the weekly newspaper "Riodose" usually meet on Wednesdays to discuss plans to cover the recent violent crimes in the state of Sinaloa associated with organized crime, corrupt officials or the ongoing war of drug dealers.
But today, overwhelmed by their own tragedy, they met to talk about security.
They were told that they should change their habits.
Two senior journalists discussed what seems safer: taking children with them to an office in which they already threw a grenade in 2009, or to leave them at home.
Security experts wrote on the board, hanging in the room, three words: enemies, neutral people, allies.
They asked journalists to name the names for each column - evidence is not needed, suspicions and internal sensations will suffice.
These are drug dealers, politicians, businessmen, journalists who are suspected of being kept by the government or cartels, a whole list of scoundrels, because of which the work on illuminating chaos in Mexico is becoming dangerous.
Violence does not give a respite, and among the corpses that are multiplying in the country, more and more journalists: according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, at least 25 since President Enrico Pena Nieto took office in December 2012, 589 people after the attacks and threats are under federal protection, and this year at least seven people were killed in seven states.
Among the latter - their publisher and inspirer, co-founder of "Riyodose" Javier Valdes Cardenas.
"The biggest mistake is to live in Mexico and be a journalist," Valdes wrote in one of his many books on violent drug-related crimes.
His absence is felt very keenly, although his presence is everywhere - a large picture of Valdes showing his middle finger, with the words "Justice" hanging on the facade of the Riodos building, two reporters in 30 years, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez wearing t-shirts that show his smile, face with glasses or his Panama brand.
The seminar takes place less than two months after his death, journalists discuss their common trauma, their nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although in 2010 the office of the special federal prosecutor was organized to investigate journalistic cases, so far, according to the Committee for the Protection of Journalists, only two cases have been investigated.
As with most of the thousands of homicides committed each year related to drug trafficking and organized crime, journalists' killers are rarely brought to trial.
Journalists "Riodos" insist that they will write about the violence in Sinaloa, although they are heartbroken, although around now it is much more dangerous.
Without information about the killers, without justice from talking about security at meetings, there is little benefit, "says Ibarra.
"It's very stupid to waste time at this seminar," he says.
"Until we know the reason, we suspect everyone."
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left the office of Riodos in the capital city of Culiacan.
He managed to drive only a couple of blocks before his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men, he was dragged out of the car and fired at him 12 times, probably because of the newspaper's name - which means "Twelfth River".
The shooter left in his car and broke it nearby.
Valdes was 50 years old.
He had a wife and two adult children.
Rumors usually disperse quickly in Culiacan.
But about Valdez, almost everyone is silent.
Since Guzman was arrested and extradited to the United States in January last year, Sinaloa has become one of the bloodiest battlefields in the country, as rival factions are struggling to fill the vacuum that has arisen.
Let's not say that one or more people are killed in the streets of Sinaloa every day, or that the cemetery is filled with decorated two-story mausoleums of drug-carrying malls, which are larger than those of many living people.
Let's forget for a moment that the state of "tranquility" is simply when one of the cartels takes control of the seaside state with important ports and drug trafficking routes leading to the United States.
Despite this and the fact that Valdes was well aware of the dangers of his work, Ismail Bokorkes, a 60-year-old co-founder and director of Riyodos, is crushed by a sense of guilt for failing to protect his friend.
He thinks that the murder was helped by two mistakes.
First, in February, an interview was published with Damaso Lopez, leader of one of the rival factions of the cartel, which is at war with Guzman's sons.
The publication could anger the sons, people who were supposedly members of the gang, bought up all copies of the publication as soon as they were delivered to the kiosks.
The second mistake was that he did not force Valdes to leave his country for his own safety after another newspaper was captured that wrote about the same story.
Valdes was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his murder was regarded as another milestone in the development of violence against journalists in Mexico.
He was so long gone from danger, his friends and colleagues thought that he would always be.
He was an experienced reporter in Noroest and in 2003, together with five colleagues founded "Riodos", selling his 50-dollar shares.
In Sinaloa, "it was impossible to engage in journalism without touching on the subject of drugs," said Bohorkes.
Over time, the newspaper earned the reputation of a bold and honest publication, sales and advertising revenues grew.
Journalists liked that they could publish bold reports without fear of censorship, and readers were attracted to the fact that in this edition they could read about what no one else dared to write about.
Eight years after its founding, Riodos received the prestigious Maria Moores Cabo Prize for reporting in Latin America.
In the same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award for courage in investigating drug trafficking in Mexico, wherever he led.
He frankly admitted that he was scared.
"I want to live on," he said at the CPJ award ceremony.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa - "this is a way of life," he said in October last year in an interview with Rompevento TV.
"You have to accept the tasks that fall on you as a journalist - either way, or you just play the fool."
I do not want to be asked: "What did you do when there were so many deaths around ... why did not you tell me what was going on?"
Employees of "Riodos" miss Valdes, a joker who cursed like a stevedore in the port, a friend, generous with hugs and tips, a teacher who knew how to hang himself alive.
They relied on the order that he had established.
He had to always wear his hat.
He had to go to El Guayabo, the bar opposite the office, and always sit there at the same table.
Now they ask: did he lose his love for the once-established order?
His death made them also doubt their calculations of how best to do their work and stay alive.
"They do not like it when you understand their wives, children, in their legal business and in underground airfields for the transport of drugs.
"These things were beyond the line," said Bohorkes.
The result, even at the best of times, was a high level of self-censorship and a desire for self-preservation.
We must believe our instincts.
Stay away from what smells bad.
The problem, says the editor of "Riodos" Andres Villareal, is that "the sense of smell can be deceived ... and then what happens to Javier happens."
The old rules, he says, and others, no longer operate in Sinaloa - as in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states, where there is a poisonous mixture of lucrative smuggling routes, weak state institutions and corrupt officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
In a room where the employees of the "Riodos" gathered for security training, it suddenly turned out to be forbidden to make cell phones: a few days before it became known that spyware programs that are sold exclusively to governments are used in Mexico to monitor journalists and public activists.
Outside, two policemen are hiding in the shade of a tree from the 104-degree heat (40 degrees Celsius).
They were given the task of the state government to guard the office of "Riodos", which is located in a four-story building in the bourgeois quarter of Culiacan.
Some journalists half-jokingly asked if these policemen were not included in those 50 percent of the servants of the order, about whom the governor himself said that they can not be trusted.
A few months ago, journalists went to the mountainous terrain, which is de facto under the control of gangs of drug dealers.
In the nearest issue, "Riodos" counted on three main topics.
This is the murder in Sinaloa brother of former boxing champion Julio Cesar Chavez.
They also had exposure of government spending concentrated in the governor's hometown.
And there was a group kidnapping in one of Culiacan's most expensive restaurants, a block from the prosecutor's office.
Officially, it was not announced who was kidnapped or how it happened, so it was necessary to be careful when it's time to write about what everyone in the city knew: that it was a favorite restaurant of both drug dealers and authorities.
One of their journalists learned from open databases that the restaurant was registered in the name of a politician belonging to the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), which dominated all levels of government for almost the entire past century.
Recently, against several governors from PRI, there have been high-profile allegations of corruption.
Villarreal asked journalists to write about previous incidents in this restaurant, including when the son of El Chapo Guzmane slipped away from the military raid.
A few months ago, readers would look for a Valdez column with the most reliable information about the abduction.
"Previously, we would already know what happened," says Villareal, 46, for his lean physique nicknamed "El Flaco."
"Today all channels of communication with our sources are broken."
Valdes' office is now used as a warehouse for posters and stickers with protests against the murders of journalists, because employees have become what they never thought to become: activists speaking on behalf of the press.
The journalist Miriam Ramirez took several posters and went the next morning to a demonstration at the local prosecutor's office, dedicated to another journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared in Michoacn in the west of the country three days after Valdes was killed.
They found a burnt body, and the authorities said that it was he, based on DNA tests.
Throughout the country, journalists began to speak out louder, organize protests and write "SOS Press" on the sidewalks and walls of houses.
On this day, Director Bohorekes was in Washington, trying to secure international support for the demand for justice in the Valdez case.
At a meeting with the governor of Sinaloa, the day after Valdes' murder, Ramirez accused the authorities of spying on journalists and ordering their murders for telling the truth.
After that, she asked not to give her more tasks to cover the activities of the government, fearing that anger would damage her objectivity.
Valdes said many times that journalists in Mexico are "surrounded" by organized crime, its accomplices in the government and indifferent society.
In his latest book, Narco-Journalism, he wrote that reporters are being killed not just by gangs of drug dealers, but by orders of politicians and security services who are in collusion with organized crime.
Press Committee "Articulo 19" believes that half of the attacks on journalists last year were committed by order of police and government officials.
"In Mexico, you die because they want to shut you up," Ramirez said.
Of course, murders frighten people.
Everyone remembers the death of the blogger Mary Elizabeth Macias six years ago in the northern border state of Tamaulipas.
A note was written on her body, supposedly written on behalf of the Zetas cartel: "I'm here because of my articles."
The computer keyboard and headphones lay next to her severed head.
Some publications preferred to close down, as the newspaper "El Norte" in the northern border state of Chihuahua after in March its correspondent Miroslav Brich was killed.
Others continue to hold on like El Manyana from Nuevo Laredo after the assassination of her leader in 2004.
In 2010, "Diario Ciudad Juarez" publicly appealed to drug cartels through an editorial on the front page, entitled "What do you want from us?"
Some journalists left their native states or even the country.
This is a painful decision.
In exile, it is difficult to find a job, and they still look out for danger on the streets.
And sometimes they are killed, as it obviously happened with photographer Ruben Espinosa, who was killed in 2015 along with four women in an apartment in Mexico three months after fled from Veracruz.
Those who remain and continue to work, daily balance between risky decisions.
Ibarra - who once dreamed of being a poet - admits that he is afraid to write about drug trafficking.
"Mexico is going to hell, and that's why I became a journalist," he says.
Last Friday, at midnight, when the last issue was already ready for printing, the publishers of "Riyodos" sat on the sidewalk near the office and drank beer when suddenly their phones rang simultaneously.
A series of skirmishes between rival gangs and security forces near the resort town of Mazatlan left behind, according to confirmed data, 19 corpses.
The war continued to flare up, as promised in a series of messages from cartels discovered in the area.
Sitting on the sidewalk, they through the mobile phone posted news on the website "Riyodos."
The next day I had to redo the first page.
Nearby, sirens howled - another shootout in the vicinity.
Bohorkes looked to see whether the policemen guarding them were ready for defense.
If they were frightened, they did not show it.
Sitting under the huge portrait of the deceased founder of their newspaper, whose middle finger was on display for the whole of Sinaloa, the staff of "Riodose" continued his business.
"How can you think about closing," said Bohorkes, "if on the very day when Javier was killed, the intern asked me to send her to the street to do a report?"
The dinosaur used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, it seems to be a statue, though horrifying.
Researchers said that the first found remains of an incredible creature the size of a rhinoceros, discovered by a Canadian miner, have survived so well that experts called it "Mona Lisa among dinosaurs."
It was so well preserved that they even could determine that the color of its scaly skin was reddish-brown - and say that it had, in some way, a "dark past".
In a report published in the journal "Contemporary Biology", it was described as "the best preserved of the Thyreofor in the history of the finds and one of the best specimens of the dinosaur in the world."
This fossil is a newly discovered specimen of the nodosaur, which lived in the middle of the Cretaceous period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
His incredible good state stunned researchers who call him "really wonderful."
This herbivore is the best-preserved fossil of its kind in the history of the finds, according to articles in the National Geographic journal.
He was found by Sean Funk when he was working at the Millennium Salloc Mill mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, in Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He stumbled upon something that seemed to be different from the surrounding rock, and decided to look more closely.
The fossil discovered by him was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Palaeontological Museum.
For the next six years, work was carried out on the detection of an animal inside an earthen block weighing 2500 pounds (1100 kilograms).
Now that all this hard work is done, the finished result can be demonstrated.
"You just have to squint a little, and you can almost believe that he is sleeping," said lead author Caleb Brown, research fellow at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontology Museum, where the creation is being shown.
"It will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best-preserved specimens of dinosaurs - Mona Lisa among dinosaurs."
Studying his skin, the researchers found that this herbivore, despite the fact that it was covered with a shell and resembled a walking tank, appeared to have been exposed to considerable danger from carnivorous dinosaurs.
This dinosaur covered with a powerful shell used red-and-white camouflage to hide from predators, and applied a protective technique known as protective paint, which is also used by many animals of our day.
This would allow him to quickly merge with the environment and avoid meeting enemies, experts say, suggesting that he was hunted by larger dinosaurs.
This 110-million-year-old creature, belonging to the family of the nodosaurs, was widely covered in print in May, and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Palaeontological Museum.
Scientists have already studied the animal and gave it the name Borealopelta markmitchelli in honor of the laboratory assistant Mark Mitchell, one of the group's members, who spent more than 7,000 hours on his painstaking excavation.
The surprising safety of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and the international group of scientists to document the pattern and shape of scales and armor plates on his body.
They discovered a protective coloration, a common method of protection in the animal kingdom, which means that the creature's upper was darker than its underside.
Although the protective coloration is well distributed, the discovery was a surprise, because the size of the Borealopelta dinosaur is much larger than the living animals with protective coloring.
It can be assumed that carnivorous dinosaurs were so actively hunting for this dinosaur that evolution preferred to camouflage confrontation as a way of survival.
But most modern animals with protective coloring - for example, deer, zebra or battleship - are much smaller and are more accessible prey, which indicates that the nosedosaur had to fight seriously for survival.
"A serious threat from predators for a massive, dinosaur covered with a powerful shell, shows how dangerous were the predatory dinosaurs of the Cretaceous period," Brown said.
The chemical analysis of organic compounds in the scales of the dinosaur also indicates that its skin should have been reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal, seeking information about his life, including the preserved contents of his digestive tract, to find out what he ate during his last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into the river and was carried into the sea, where it sank and fell back down to the bottom of the ocean.
At that time, Alberta was as warm as now in the south of Florida, and the rivers and oceans, most likely, spread much deeper into the land than now.
"This nodosaur is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered with preserved scaly skin, and at the same time completely preserved in three dimensions, preserving the original form of the animal," Brown said.
"As a result, now the animal looks almost the same as it looked then, in the Early Cretaceous.
You do not need to resort especially to the imagination to recreate it, you just have to squint slightly, and you can almost believe that he is sleeping. "
The Cretaceous period is an epoch when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs, standing on two legs, wandered around the Earth.
Although the most remarkable of them, the tyrannosaurus rex, lived millions of years later than the Borealopelta, one of his menacing ancestors could hunt the thyroid.
These include acrokantosaurus, a monster 38 feet long (11.5 meters) weighing six tons.
Scientists whose recent discoveries are published in the journal "Contemporary Biology" believe that Borealopelta was after death dumped into the sea and mummified in mud.
The creature was found by Sean Funk when he was working at the Millennium Mill near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, in Canada, on March 21, 2011.
According to the museum staff, this is the best-preserved tierophore in the world, along with the skin and armor, and it is intact, from the muzzle to the hip bones.
On average, these creatures reached approximately 18 feet (five meters) in length and weighed up to 3000 pounds (1,300 kilograms).
Their characteristic feature was two twenty-inch spikes protruding from their shoulders.
Researchers believe that this herbivore practitioner has treaded heavily on what is now Canada, until the flooded river carried him to the open sea.
But the underwater burial of the dinosaur preserved its shell to the smallest detail.
The fossilized remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the remains of the skin still cover the bumpy armor plates along the skull of the dinosaur.
As Michael Grechko wrote in an article for the National Geographic magazine, such a degree of preservation is "rare, like winning the lottery."
The longer I look at him, the more striking he seems.
The fossilized skin remains till now cover the tuberous armor plates, which dot the skull of the animal.
His right front leg is stretched along the side, five fingers on it are turned upwards.
I can count the scales on his sole. "
