The emergence of similarities: the artist creates portraits using the DNA of Chelsea Manning
In the center of the hall in the Friedman Gallery in New York from the ceiling on the wire hang people's faces - white, black and brown, all something subtly similar to each other.
These 30 portraits were created by the artist Heather Dewey-Harborg from the smears from the cheeks and hair trim sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent trimmings from Fort-Leavenworth prison, where the former intelligence analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for the famous transfer of confidential diplomatic cables on the WikiLeaks website.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called "The emergence of similarity."
This is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey Harbor, whose art unites technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a female transsexual and famous dissident, whom Barack Obama mitigated the verdict just three days before the end of his presidency.
Having analyzed the DNA obtained from Manning with a computer program and used it to create three-dimensional portraits of persons that could be in people with such a genome, Dewey-Harborg created a deep, if not easy-to-comprehend manifesto dedicated not only to the plasticity of DNA data - to various ways of interpreting them and the incoherent determinism of these interpretations - but to the notion of identity.
Manning, who was born with the name of Bradley Edward, but from adolescence openly said that she considers herself a woman, in 2013 she was sentenced to 20 episodes, including six violations of the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
Her photographs in prison were inaccessible, so only one of her photos was known: a grainy black-white selfie, in which Manning in a platinum-tinted wig, clearly uncomfortable, sitting behind the wheel of a car, with this photo and associate her.
In 2015, Dewey-Harborg successfully completed its 2012 project "Visions of Strangers" with great success.
In it, the artist created portraits of unknown people with the help of forensic evidence like cigarette butts and chewing gum, isolating DNA from this garbage and creating images of how these people might look.
And then she received an email from Paper Magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning in jail and wanted a portrait to illustrate the article," Dewey-Hagborg explained at the preview of the new press exhibition.
At that time, Chelsea could not be visited and photographed, so they contacted her and asked if she would like to get a portrait created from her DNA.
In this unusual way, the artist and her imprisoned muse became pen pals and exchanged several letters for two years.
They even wrote the comic book "Depressed Images", illustrated by Shoili Canungo, who portrayed how in the future the president will mitigate the punishment of Chelsea and she will be able to visit the exhibition personally.
The fact that Obama really decided to release Manning just days after the book was published was a pleasant surprise after seven hard years in a military prison in Kansas.
There is something deep and strong in the fact that the exhibition opens right now, when Donald Trump declares war on people disclosing sensitive information in the government, and devises new ways to kindle the feud on Twitter, which he is called upon to mitigate.
When Dewey-Harborg was asked about the coincidence of this all in time, she said that "by chance nothing happens."
In the artist's statement, written on the wall of the gallery, Manning's huge signature downstairs (with a heart instead of a dot over the "i" in her surname) calls for an end to "automatic separation based on sex, race, sexual orientation and culture."
On the opposite side is its mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar of C, G, and A penciled out.
Including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as artistically exquisitely expressed artist), Dewey-Harborg hoped to show how we are all remarkably similar, at least in terms of their biological structure.
"I hope to explain to people that our genome does not determine what we are, how open the genetic data is for interpretation and how subjective it is," said Dewey-Harbor, her 2007 video work "False Memories" is also exhibited here.
"DNA data can tell us a lot of different stories, and 30 of these stories are here."
The last part of the exhibition, which fits in one room, is the above-mentioned novel in comic books.
On it, Manning in the style of King Kong appears above the US Correctional Barracks building with a loudspeaker in his hand.
"If they kill your speech, they will win," is written there.
"Therefore, never stop."
"This is a direct quote from a letter she wrote to me," says the artist, who greets us from Philadelphia.
"I still have goosebumps when I talk about it."
Manning had not yet seen the exhibition in person - as it was prophetically portrayed in comic books - but when she comes, she will be greeted by masks in the center of the room, her own genomic simulacra, gathered like crowds of protesters.
This is also done deliberately, like everything at the exhibition up to the height (5-2, Manning's growth), on which genetic haplogroups were drawn with a pencil.
"I would have hung them on the walls before, but now I wanted them to look like a crowd of people," says Dewey Harbor about portraits.
"I wanted them to be like the mass movement that formed around Chelsea, as the movement that stood and for its liberation."
