Startups that will help your company not become another "Uber"
Amy Errett wanted to assess the level of satisfaction amongst employees of her startup in e-commerce, but the polls did not work.
The answers were often vague, useless or, worse, insincere.
And even though she promised anonymity, some employees did not trust this process.
"He was never consistent and objective," said Errett, managing a San Francisco-based 75-person company, Madison Reed, which deals with e-commerce in hair care.
Therefore, she appealed to third parties for help.
Now there is a new kind of start-ups in the field of work with personnel that help companies find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software designed to measure the involvement of employees, they allow companies to do quick surveys, access specific teams and demographic groups, offer employees anonymity and hot lines for complaints, and in some cases allow informants to pass top management and contact the directorate directly.
"Now we have tools like Strava and Fitbit for health monitoring, and where is Fitbit for your company?" Says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of the Glint start-up company in Redwood City, whose analytical programs are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Herrett said that she has achieved a greater understanding of what her employees think and feel for three years using Glint.
In addition to express polls and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers a company heat card and shows in visual form, which departments have more complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, which allows them to understand why.
The companies are gradually realizing that they need to monitor the situation in the workplace, otherwise they will become another "Uber", who was involved in the scandal when a former employee published a blog post describing the aggressive situation in which those who expressed dissatisfaction were punished.
For start-ups like Glint, this desire to control the situation is an opportunity for profitable business.
According to the Internet portal "Let's talk about payment", dedicated to financial technologies, the industry of global governance, regulation and compliance by 2020 can cost more than 118.7 billion dollars.
The Convercent start-up from Denver, Colorado, helping companies prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year amid the fall of Uber's reputation.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, among the customers appeared "Uber".
Like "Glint", "Convercent" allows companies to send custom-made polls to staff opinions, collect confidential responses in real time and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages, which allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if the top manager is affected, complaints go directly to the directorate.
"The court of public opinion seized power from the inspectors," said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that the company mistreates employees or behaves unethically, even if the inspectors do not intervene, the company may face costly consequences in the form of boycotts from customers, outflow of employees and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a chain of restaurants with more than 25,000 employees in 500 establishments, used Convercent for more than a year to ensure that employees are aware of the rules and procedures and offer an easy way to contact the company's head office.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to look up the phone number or email of the head office, file an official complaint and hope that they will take it seriously.
Often this was a frightening and awkward experience, said James Vitrano, the head of the legal department of Ruby Tuesday, who said that there was no normal way to track employee complaints.
Now, when the company uses the Convercent service, problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states - such as discrimination, harassment and unfair remuneration - can be detected and dealt with more quickly.
"I can approach a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the situation of employees," said Vitrano, who manages the risk management group of the Ruby Tuesday network.
"And we protect our shareholders from litigation with employees."
According to Quinland, the companies began to take a more serious attitude toward ethics, values and employee involvement in 2002, after the accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed due to ethical violations as a result of the Enron Enron case.
But it was only when "social networks got mass spread" that companies realized that they could not keep their dirty laundry from spreading viral in the network.
"Before using technologies to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy," he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies with a regular fee for using their products.
This is a business model and an opportunity that was approved by venture investors who supported both start-ups.
In February, Convercent received funding of $ 10 million from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the company's total capital to $ 47 million.
Glint received $ 10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, resulting in a total capital of $ 60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
The growing volume of research demonstrates that today's employees expect more from their jobs than they did before.
In markets with tough competition, such as Silicon Valley, high salaries and interesting projects - this is just the minimum required.
Employees want to feel that they are accepted and appreciated, and that they devote their time to a company with a positive mission.
"When people are happy to work in a company, they feel they are being heard, and that the work they do is producing results, they are more likely to make such a company successful," says Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee satisfaction at LinkedIn, using both Convercent and Glint.
Investors receive income when businesses from their portfolio are doing well, businesses are doing well when employees are committed and involved.
If analytical tools of the third party promise to increase the loyalty and involvement of employees, it is not surprising that they find support.
According to experts on culture in the workplace, it is important to have data on the involvement of employees.
But the data are useless until the company's trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it can create the impression that change is coming.
And if the changes do not come quickly enough, or do not come at all, frustration can develop, and employees will lose interest.
"If you are going to ask for 4000 offers, you should be prepared to conduct 4,000 conversations," says Russell Rath, president of consulting at the management company Kotter International, who has seen companies make the mistake of relying too much on data collection.
"Because if you do not go to the end, employees will guess:" Did you really hear me?
Do you care?
And if you do not care, why should not I care? "
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to take action on the same day that someone reports a problem with the help of Glint.
And, after collecting feedback from employees dissatisfied with the speed of decision making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce a communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new knowledge about its employees and hopes that in the long term this knowledge will help it to more effectively retain employees in an industry known for high turnover.
"If you do not try to create a culture of transparency, you will lose people," Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
And if you lose customers, you lose the company.
