Create a novel-comics: One castle in English history
In the recent past, Scotty's tiny castle was filmed in the music video "Squeeze", and in the 70s and 80s served as a refuge for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years from his cozy place in the valley of the river Bewl in the county of Kent, he watched the turbulent history around, and now inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshireman with a shock of hair and a penchant for historical documents, a novel comic book.
"It seems to me, it's so beautiful - to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago," he says enthusiastically.
"You feel it so personally when you hold this letter in your hand."
"Castle in England" covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Guardian era and tells about the families who lived in Scotney, each story illustrated by one of the young British artists - Isaac Lenkevich, Brioni May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
This is not the first book of Rhodes, which is based on archival data: in 2014 he wrote "The teeth of a dead man and other stories" - a collection of materials from the documents of the British Library, this project suddenly touched him to the depths of his soul.
"I could be touched simply by a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for Jacobites," he says.
"It's a fingerprint of his finger"
And letters always smell of smoke, because in those days fire was lit for lighting.
And in 300 years, in the future, it seems to you that you are also there.
Oh, how I love archives! "
For a person embraced by such a passion for old papers, get support from the National Foundation and the English art council and live in the castle for four months ("To be honest, I got a little tired out there") seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent days studying the "new" Victorian castle, walking through the archives and viewing the numerous treasures of the estate and antiques - for example, the heads of hyenas on the walls or bottles that had lain in the ditch for centuries.
He walked through the park and through the ruins of the old castle, talking with foresters, gardeners and sometimes with artists working on illustrations for his book.
Then at night he "drank whiskey and sat down to write."
The history of Scotney Castle is not very well understood, because the National Foundation received full access to it only in 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the employees only began to understand the archive, which he describes as "something that aristocrats have been dumping in the attic for centuries."
Diaries, letters from the times of the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: "You think that land disputes are boring," Rhodes says, "but two families fought for this birch.
It happens so, guys! "
In some stories of the collection, the castle becomes the starting point for wider research in English history: for example, in Rabotnik, the hero leaves the newly constructed castle to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
"There is information about the riot that occurred in the castle in 1380, in a book called" Knightly families of Kent and Sussex, "says Rhodes.
"The peasant uprising began in these places, and I thought that rebellion is a suitable beginning.
Maybe they were connected? "
Other subjects are closely related to the history of the castle - for example, "Priest", which tells about the Jesuit priest, whom the Darrel family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or Smuggler, about the eighteenth-century smuggler Arthur Darrel, who is believed to have staged his own funeral, stuffing the coffin with stones (this was discovered a few years later when the coffin was dug up).
Darrells are Rhodes' favorite family from all that Scotney inhabited: "The gentlemen seem to have been a perfect crook, always getting into debt and spending money on things they could not afford.
In different generations, Darrel men solved their problems with debts, marrying rich elderly women - I imagine them as a company of handsome guys who are able to care for the heirs of big fortunes. "
After graduating from the castle, Rhodes looks for other opportunities to get a unique writing experience.
He spent two weeks in the Finnish wilderness, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elyamyamyaka - a place where in the early 20th century there was a sanatorium, and then it was again overgrown with forest.
But Scotney remains for him a special place.
"It was sad for me to leave," he says.
"I felt like this: dammit, I have to go back to real life again."
