Andrei Okhlopkov was transferred from the cosmodrome
As it became known to Kommersant, the technical director of the spaceport Vostochny Andrei Okhlopkov started work at the Khrunichev State Space Research and Production Center (SCNPC).
Previously, he was de facto engaged in the construction of the Vostochny cosmodrome, but because of disagreements with the leadership of the Center for the Operation of Ground and Space Infrastructure (CENSCI), he was transferred to an enterprise in Moscow Fili, where he will coordinate production.
Mr. Okhlopkov will not be a replacement in the position of a technical director, most likely they will be abolished, and the functionality will be distributed among the CENSC divisions.
The fact that the technical director of the East and the deputy director general of the Center for Economic Development Andrei Okhlopkov moved to the Khrunichev Khrunichev Space Research Center was told by the top managers of several space industry enterprises, as well as an employee of the government apparatus.
"He has been working at the new post for several weeks," the interlocutors of Kommersant clarified in the industry.
Get a quick comment CENSC on Thursday failed, and Mr. Okhlopkov himself for comment was unavailable.
However, Kommersant's information was officially confirmed at the SCNC.
He made the decision to move to the position of Director for Production Coordination, - said at the enterprise. "Andrei Okhlopkov fully accomplished the task assigned to him to provide the starting minimum for the first launch at the Vostochny Spaceport.
Mr. Okhlopkov moved to work at the CENSCI in 2013, having a service in the space forces, in particular at Baikonur, and in Plesetsk - at the "northern" cosmodrome he held the post of first deputy commander in the rank of colonel.
In 2009, Andrei Okhlopkov became a figurant of the criminal case.
The investigation accused him of bribery: ostensibly from his submission, regional businessmen were paid for kickbacks of state orders, but they did not fulfill their obligations to clean up the detachable parts of the launch vehicles in the Arkhangelsk region and the Komi Republic.
In 2012 the jury found him innocent.
The responsibilities for technological development entrusted to him were extended to different projects, but the main one was the construction of a cosmodrome in the Far East.
Headed then the Federal Space Agency Oleg Ostapenko in an interview with Kommersant bluntly said that the situation on the East "was critical already in October 2013".
The matter is that when planning a strategic mistake was made: the completion of the construction and the first launch of the Soyuz-2.1 rocket was planned at the same time - the end of 2015.
To carry out the launch before the end of the year, the construction was completed six months earlier and the deadlines were removed from December to July 2015.
To speed up the process, we had to go to the trick: the specialists of the Center for Standardization and Standardization began to conduct parallel installation of technological equipment on unfinished facilities.
The main supporter of this idea was Andrei Okhlopkov.
Despite the risks that existed, and yet the transfer happened (instead of December 2015, the "Union" flew only on April 28, 2016), this idea proved to be justified, says a Kommersant source at the cosmodrome: "Otherwise, we would still not have launched a single launch from the East, but we would be engaged in construction."
Deputy Prime Minister Dmitry Rogozin, who oversees the creation of the cosmodrome, jokingly called Andrei Okhlopkov his "space Susanin," but he almost always asked for information about the construction process.
I remember Mr. Okhlopkov and straightforwardness: for example, in an interview with Kommersant, he proposed to deprive the Federal Agency for Special Construction (Spetsstroy) of the status of a sole performer in the East and work directly with subcontractors: "Why should we put all our eggs in one basket of Spetsstroy?"
This idea found support in the government.
Since 2017, CENCI has assumed the responsibility of the general contractor, in order to complete the construction and installation works at the launch and technical complex planned for the fourth quarter.
According to Kommersant's information, the reason for Okhlopkov's transition to a new job was disagreement with the management of the TsENKI regarding ways to complete the construction of facilities and complexes of the cosmodrome, as well as methods of working with subcontractors.
"It was decided that it would be better for everyone," says one of the top managers involved in the construction of the East.
The employee of the government apparatus, in turn, calls the decision strange: "He was one of the best specialists, it will not be easy to find him an equivalent substitute."
According to "Kommersant", this is not required: the post of the technical director of the cosmodrome will be abolished, and its functions will be scattered across the divisions of the Center for Economic Research.
