Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can help ease the IBD.
Red meat and chocolate is considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent studies suggest the opposite: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help alleviate the symptoms of those who suffer from inflammatory bowel diseases.
This incurable disease, which affects approximately 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to mitigate symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers at the University of Washington have determined that the main amino acid of tryptophan protein promotes the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that the immune cells in the intestine make sure that harmful microbes coming in with food do not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of triggering an inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body and without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too violated in the direction of inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel disease.
Experiments have shown that in mice that have a certain bacterium in the intestine, there are increasing tolerance cells.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan - one of the building blocks of protein - to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between one kind of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri, which is part of the normal intestinal microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophan was contained in the diet of mice, the more these immune cells they had. "
He suggested that the same would work in humans: the combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet can contribute to a more tolerant and less inflammatory environment in the intestine.
Postdoctor Dr. Louise Cervantes-Barraganvas, studying a variety of immune-enhancing immune cells, found that in one group of experimental mice these cells were, and another group that belonged to the same line but was kept separate did not.
She suggested that the difference may be caused by the microbiome of the intestine of mice-the communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the intestinal cells of the mice were sequenced, and six species of bacteria were found present in mice that had immune cells but were absent in mice that did not have them.
Mice grown in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this kind of immune cells received L. reuteri, and the immune cells they had appeared.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers raised L. reuteri in a liquid medium and then transferred small portions of the liquid - without bacteria - to the underdeveloped immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells have become cells that increase tolerance.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of tryptophan processing, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the food of mice, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the level of tryptophan was halved, the number of cells also fell by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that people have the same tolerance-enhancing cells as in mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether byproducts of tryptophan from L. reuteri contribute to the development of cells in humans in the same way as in mice, but in people with inflammatory bowel disease, defects in genes associated with tryptophan have been found.
She says: "Perhaps the development of these cells we need to strengthen, since inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri can potentially lead to an expansion of their population. "
