Props for the White House cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
According to the records of the armed forces provided to TIME magazine, the decision of the White House last month to bring a Marine helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers as much as $ 24,000.
The white-and-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as the "Marine One" when the president is on board, was the central element of the July 17th White House event that showed US construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials inspected technological products from all of the fifty states.
A helicopter made in Connecticut was parked next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Squadron of Marine Corps Helicopters (HMX-1), the department responsible for helicopter control, the White House Military Department ordered the presence of the helicopter in a private order, or "FRAGO", just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South lawn on the occasion of an "unusual" event.
"I just wanted you to make sure that you are aware of, because this is an unusual event widely publicized in the press," wrote the commander of the HMX-1 in an e-mail to his chief, the first deputy chief of aviation for the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter stated that the helicopter would arrive to the South Lawn at about 7 am on July 17 to attend the event scheduled for 3 pm and stay there until the lawn was released between 6 and 9 pm on the same day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for a return flight in accordance with the restrictions on working hours.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, and the security officers of the unit remained near the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the records received by TIME magazine, it remains unclear whether the second crew was required as a result.
The Hatch law prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the measure does not contradict this resolution.
"Among other things, we asked whether this was a violation of Hatch's law, and we were told that there was not," wrote the commander.
"It seems that you have nowhere to go," the deputy chief replied.
The event "Made in America" was announced by the White House as an official event, and Hatch's law did not apply to him.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the president made efforts to promote health reform, which was then in development in the Senate, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as "Marine One" and "Air Force One" for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are instructed to use them for travel.
But to ask them solely in the interests of photo opportunities is unusual.
Trump already became the subject of discussions in February, when the presidential plane drove in the background during his first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was flooded with reports of complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessor.
"The White House is delighted with the" Made in America "show, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials," said White House spokeswoman Lindsey Walters.
HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington metropolitan area and on the South Lawn to train transportation of the president of the United States to the White House to within an inch.
When Trump in early July was at the G-20 summit in Germany, the HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight made for the event "Made in America" was credited to the crew on the basis of the necessary training flights for the month.
Helicopters of the unit that day also flew 11 extra hours in the framework of "non-resident tasks to provide support."
According to the White House, the taxpayers did not cover expenses for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A representative of the company "Sikorsky" said that the company did not participate in organizing a helicopter demonstration on the South Lawn.
The HMX-1 does not keep account of the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent for the event.
But, according to the hourly rates of the Ministry of Defense for 2017 fiscal year, the rate of reimbursement of the Ministry of Defense for VH-3D is 24,380 US dollars per hour of flight.
The unit records that the time of the aircraft in the air was 30 minutes in each direction from its airfield at the Kuantico Marines air base in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using the helicopter is much lower than this rate.
"Calculating the cost for taxpayers, based on the approximate refund rate, is completely wrong," says Walters.
"These approximate rates include personnel, maintenance and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual appropriations."
According to a study conducted in 2015 by the RAND Corporation, the reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but, indeed, take into account the cost of fuel, services and costs specified in the contract.
At that time, the former White House spokesman, Sean Spicer, spoke out in defense of the use of the helicopter for the event.
"The idea is to showcase things done in America this week," Spicer said.
"And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they are contributing to national security, and that there are, I presume, hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose workplace depends on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment, the creation of which has worked so hard for so many Americans.
Therefore, of course, it is absolutely appropriate to draw attention to this. "
It was unclear if Trump was cooperating with the helicopter, inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he was exactly sitting in the driver's seat in the fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump contacted representatives of Sikorsky, joking with the press about his own fleet of company products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," the president said, "I have three of them."
