The National Union of Unqualified, Municipal and Boiler Workers (GMB) is concerned about the investment at the McVitie's factory in Glasgow
The union requires guarantees from McVitie's biscuit manufacturer managers in connection with its long-term production commitment at the Glasgow plant.
The Scottish branch of GMB reports that the company ignored the issue of future investments at the Tolkros facility.
The factory, which produces, among other products, Hobnobs and Rich Tea cookies, employs more than 500 people.
The company Pladis, the owner of McVitie's, said that over the past few years, has invested more than 5 million pounds in the facility.
The company adds that in case of any changes in the work of the facility, employees and representatives of the trade union "learn about them first."
In a letter to the head of the facility owned by the company, the Scottish branch of the GMB demanded from McVitie's reaction to the concern that funding would not be put on the modernization of production lines.
Senior organizer Drew Duffy said: "Our union members are deeply concerned that we can not get clarity from the general manager of the facility on business needs and an investment plan for the future of Tollcross."
Families have worked here for generations, and the concentration of workers is great in the local society and on the territory of Greater Glasgow, this is the most important pillar of decent work in the territory of high unemployment and social deprivation.
Thus, in terms of jobs, wages and prosperity, and against the backdrop of Brexit, the rising living wage and the chronic decline in production, the East End of Glasgow desperately needs the prosperity of production at the McVitie's factory.
According to Pladis spokesperson, "The head of the Tolcro facility just received a letter from the GMB Scottish branch just yesterday and the company will respond immediately, as we value our continued cooperation with employees and union representatives."
Two months ago we held a regular meeting in Tolkross with employees and representatives of GMB, where a number of issues were openly discussed.
We talked with employees that, like all companies operating in the most competitive and unstable economic climate, we are constantly reviewing our actions - and this applies to all our facilities and activities - in order to remain competitive.
"In recent years, we have invested more than 5 million pounds in our Tricros facility, especially in production lines and improving performance."
We are fully aware of the value of Tolcross as a production facility, and in case of any changes in the work at this facility, employees and representatives of the union will be the first to know about it. "
